				 Hindustan Paper to float subsidiary 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Nov. 26: The Union cabinet today approved Hindustan Paper Corporations proposal to set up a subsidiary company. The new entity will set up a paper mill at Jagdishpur in Uttar Pradesh.																								Information and broadcasting minister P.R.Das Munshi told newspersons here that Prime Minister Manmohan Singh also placed the Eleventh Plan document before the cabinet and asked ministers to give in writing their suggestions and submissions, which would then be taken up for consideration.																								The Jagdishpur mill of Hindustan Paper will cost around Rs 3,241 crore. 																								The company will hold a 51 per cent stake in the subsidiary, while the balance 49 per cent will be raised from the capital market through an initial public offering.																								The government will grant a loan of Rs 255 crore to Hindustan Paper and create the post of a full-time managing director for the new company. The subsidiary will produce value-added paper. 																								The government will set up a special purpose vehicle (SPV) in the form of a co-operative society under the Multi-State Cooperative Societies Act 1984. The SPV will grow farm-based products needed as raw material for the company.																								The cabinet also approved the financial restructuring of Bharat Heavy Plates and Vessels (BHPV) and its takeover by Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited.																								According to the restructuring plan, the government will write off loans and interest amounting to Rs 415 crore until March this year. 																								It will also settle all outstanding liabilities of BHPV amounting to around Rs 264 crore.
